V2.0 (2017-11-04)

Simply added a schematic for easier imaginize the difference between the height of 20mm and 22mm.
Last weeks I printed only with this duct, and I am very satisfied.

V2.0 (2017-10-07)

I have completely redesigned the fan duct and now it works as I imagine.

Improvements to old version:
(old version is in zip-file)

  • easier to print
  • bigger tube
  • better air flow at all holes
  • corner bevelled to optimize the airflow and reduce resistance
  • improved blower-connector ("disabled" the whistle-sound; now rushes only)
  • better holding in blower

I have added two versions with different distances from blower bottom and duct bottom (20mm and 22mm). The 20mm version has more distance to print bed, the 22mm is 2mm lower.

It works very good for me at the moment.
Please let me know, if it works for you too.

V1.0 (2017-09-27)

(First and old version)
This is a combined redesign from this https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2186878 and this https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2234778

I loved the bigger holes and the compact design from the first one and the nearly full circular airflow from almost all diections from the second.

So I designed a combined fan duct.
It fits perfectly in my blower and the nozzle is in the middle.
I am also satisfied with the relative height to nozzle.
Some ducts are very far down, so they had scratched the first tracks partly from the glass plate.

2017-10-02
IMPORTANT:
Actually I am testing a new design.
If it works as I imagine it, I will update this description and replace the files.
At the moment It looks good. The new one is a bit bigger, but very light and the blower is significantly quieter (had whistled before).

description.text:
The idea with Basic Trailer Project is that you can combine standard parts to make your
own trailer design. It is built with screws and nuts so you can change, upgrade, repair
or take it apart and build something else.

Twist and turn the objects so that the print fits you and your printer.

Here we have support legs. This version is motorized with one small motor
inside each leg. Switch polarity for up/down movement.
There are no limit-switches in these small legs.
You can control them with a simple ON-OFF-ON momentary switch, relay,
motorcontroller, microcontroller or whatever.
I'm going to use my homemade, Arduino-based digitalcontrol, same as I use
for my truck, forklift and other vehicles. Will make a new video when this project
is finished sometimes this winter.

Check this video how I made some useless supportlegs on my prototype trailer:
https://youtu.be/wwyBKh6TZkA
I was going to attend a truckmeeting and had to put it together with things
I had at home.

But anyway, the main goal is to make every function remote controlled.
I don't want to manually connect/disconnect trailer to truck.

title: Pergo Robo3D/R1/+ PVC Heat Chamber or Ver 3

description.text:
I love the summer because everything prints easy!
But in winter, everything is tough to print. I keep my house the same temp all year round but just a little draft is enough to make a print job a failure.

This is version 3 (See my things for the other 2 versions)
This design is my favorite because it is a game changer for a cheap heat chamber.

  • It goes on and off the printer very easy. (If you have the filament spool uploaded).
  • It stores flat against a wall. (unlike my earlier versions, they were a pain to store)
  • It's sturdier an you can lift it up out of the way if needed.
  • Simpler to print, build, and repair if needed.
  • You can use any plastic that does not have holes in it. OR modify to use glass or whatever you dream up... The real heat of this is that it allows you to mount something to the sides of the printer.

Because my modded printer can print 372 mm on the Y axis,
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2216671
my bed is longer, so my 1/2" PVC sides were 920 mm long. this design allows it to work on EVERY Robo3D printer regardless of your bed length! Just pull your glass bed to it's max in the forward and the back positions and measure. This will be the length for the side PVC pipes. I recommend that you place a tic mark at the middle. This tic is really handy when putting the plastic on. To measure out the plastic to cut, I placed the assembled frame on the floor. Place the plastic over it and use a letter sheet of paper as a guide to leave about 15" all around the outside of the frame. (See pictures). Next cut ONE slit down the middle where the top of the printer will poke out.
Cut 8 pieces of tape (I used black electrical so you could see it). I made 4 "saddles" that connect the plastic together where the slit was cut. NOTE: I have the gum sides of the tape sticking to each other. there is NO tape connecting to the printer. this allows you to take the hood off for storage.

Get it all positioned and then drill pilot holes with a drill in the indented locations on the elbows. put the plastic on and screw the screws into the drilled out holes. (I didn't cut holes so you could choose your choice of screw size.

Once all the screws are in, cut a slit on each side of front of the printer so you can flip the front plastic open to access the printer.

All is printed solid except the Elbows can be 6 shells/layers and a 12-15% in-fill.

I used PLA for all parts. Nothing ever gets that warm enough even when printing ABS to be an issue.

After printing the parts and screwing them together, we need to make the side supports bow downward a bit (see the pictures) this makes the tips fit into the top slot of the Robo3D much better. To do this, you want to heat your bed up to 90c and place the assembled side on the bed as pictured. in about a min, the PLA will heat up and allow you to bow or bed it. See how I'm pushing the "U" (or horse shoe looking item) in to the 8 mm bar in the picture. this making the U lift up and bow heated PLA.

There are no top slot covers because they are already present in my thing #2155476.
If you are not using my spool holder you can take one EndCovers.STL from 2155476 and resize it like 240 mm (a guess on length) and drill a hole in it to allow filament to pass through. or print 2 EndCovers.STL each like 115 mm ?

If you use my version 2 spool holder shown here
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2155476
Print 2 each EndCovers.STL from 2155476 with the length resized to 48.5 mm and they will meet nicely with the Side Support.STL's printed for this heat chamber.

title: Vorpal Hexapod Fidget Spinner Challenge Game

description.text:
This is an add-on accessory for the totally awesome Vorpal Combat Hexapod, If you haven't seen that yet, then this thing won't make sense, so visit there first:

  • Thing 2513566: Vorpal Combat Hexapod

I made this all open source and respectfully ask you to consider supporting the project. We successfully funded on Kickstarter with hundreds of kits sold, and now we have our own store. We have more than just the Hexapod electronics, we have all kinds of things useful for small robotics and other projects:
Vorpal Robotics Store with Hexapod Kits

  • IMPORTANT: If you opt-in to receive our store monthly newsletters you'll automatically be enrolled in a monthly prize drawing, first prize is a $100 store credit and there are lots of other smaller prizes too! Sign up for newsletters here:
  • Vorpal Store Opt-in for Prize Drawing

Why do I need this for the Hexapod?

This is a game piece for playing the "Fidget Spinner Challenge" game, played with one or more Vorpal Combat Hexapods.

Fidget Spinner Challenge Video

This is a bracket used to hold a Fidget Spinner at a good height for the robot to manipulate.

For complete game rules see the Games and Activities Page on our website.

This is a basic activity to get students used to the controls and to think about what leg motions might work best to solve the problem. There are many different ways to get the fidget spinner going.

HINT: Using "tiny step mode" is great for getting into just the right spot, but since this is a timed event, you would probably want to use a faster walk mode to get close, then only use tiny step mode at the end. This gets students used to switching back and forth between modes to solve problems.

HINT: The video shows the technique of using "fight mode" to turn the spinner, however, there are far easier ways. Experiment!

Using it For The Fidget Spinner Challenge Activity

You need to tape the Fidget Spinner Holder to the floor or table top using masking tape, duct tape, gaffer tape, etc.

Remove the plastic disk from the center of the spinner (just one side, not both). This is quite easy to do either with fingernails or a flat head screwdriver. Don't lose the extra piece though.

Press a fidget spinner into the top of the bracket (with the side you removed the piece from down). It will be reasonably stable, but can be knocked off, that's part of the game. The bracket is for a standard size spinner, if you've got a different size you may need to use double sided tape or modify the design.

Students start with Vorpal two feet away (mark the starting area to be fair). Another person times how long it takes for them to walk over and get the spinner going. You may want to have a referee who only accepts a fast enough spin (i.e. so fast that it's a blur). The person who achieves this in the shortest time wins.

Knocking the spinner off the holder results in a time penalty. Be careful!

Confessions of a Robot Designer

I originally created this totally as a joke. But I demonstrated it at two events, including Maker Faire NY, and it was a smash hit. You should see the look on kids' faces as they try to make the fidget spinner turn using the robot and gamepad (which they just got their hands about a minute earlier). I mean, they are focused! And when they get it going fast, they just light up like it was their birthday.

So, simple idea, but worked!

title: Five-Axle Stepper Motor Clock
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
I designed this clock to be small so it would fit inside a top hat. I am making a steam punk costume with a clock inside the hat and I wanted it to have visible gears. Despite the ubiquity of clocks, there is not a lot of easily accessible information on designing a clock from scratch. So, this design took weeks of research and much trial and error. This model is the result and is entirely my own design.

I did not try to make movement mechanism. Instead, I bought a stepper motor and hardware to run the motor at 1 RPM. This motor drives the second hand axle. If there is any interest, I can post more details on the electronics. However, I basically programmed an ardiuno to run the stepper motor.

The bearings in this clock are standard skateboard bearings. I got the cheapest ones I could find ($10 for 8). They are 22mm on the outside and 8mm on the inside and 7mm thick.

This version is actually a five-axle clock. I improved the design to require less gears. See the clock running in "break-In" mode here: https://youtu.be/JpaEKej01mE. You can see there is a little hitch in the gears caused by the 3D printing process. I am running the clock faster than normal to get those bumps to smooth out.

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

TAZ 6

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.4

Infill:

25

Notes:

Only a couple pieces need supports. Axles two through six are designed to be printed laying on their side. There are .2 mm of slop built into the gear spacing to reduce friction between the gears.

I used two top and bottom layers with two perimeters.

I had to use small fine-toothed triangular and round files to smooth out the main axle and the sleeves to ensure they were free spinning. Due to the natural inconsistencies of 3D printing vertical columns. You could probably reduce the amount of post print clean up by reducing the layer height. However, I wanted to print faster with a bigger layer height.

The name of the gear tells you the gear tooth could and which axle it belongs on. For example, A2G30-15 is a Axle 2 gear with a 30-tooth wheel and a 15-tooth pinion. The main axle is not numbered. However, the subsequent numbers start from that axle and are numbered going counterclockwise.

The hinge arm uses M6-100 and nut (M6-90 should be fine)

Hubs use 4x 608ZZ bearings, and 2x M8-45 and nut (M8-35 would work on the right side), and a washer or shim on the left.

2x M4-15 can be used to secure the left arm (4mm holes so they thread in). Not really sure it's necessary though. It was just done to space it to 75-80mm wide spools.

The inner hubs are 0.3mm smaller than the spool adapters to slide in and should be about 10mm smaller than the smallest spool opening. Then the adapters should be a quick print, and have some space at the flex point between the inner ring and outer tabs.

title: Yet another motorized version of the 3D Printed Marble Machine #3 powered by ESP8266 ESP-01

description.text:
This is a motorized version of the 3D Printed Marble Machine #3.

It is 60% size of the original. If you have already one printed (in this size) it can be even upgraded to the motorized version by making a hole in the middle, changing the spiral and adding the base.

The motor is 3-6V DC Small Micro Speed Reduction Geared Box Electric Motor 40RPM sold on eBay.
The main chip is ESP8266 ESP-01 with NodeMCU Lua. The speed can be adjusted by PWM regulation. The power is supplied via micro USB so any phone adapter can be used. A 5V to 3.3V Step-Down Power Supply Module AMS1117-3.3 LDO 800MA is used to power the chip. ESP8266 drives the motor via NPN transistor protected by diode.

Of course the machine can be programmed to be triggered by any event. This version can be triggered via web browser and is also scheduled.

For more technical details and code see: https://github.com/vsky279/marble-marchine-ESP8266

To make this work, you'll need to print the gasket with flexible filament, like Ninjaflex. Inset the gasket into the rim of the upper sphere, and tightly bolt them together with six M5 x 30mm bolts. Attach a tether to the handle on the shell, fill the bathysphere with heavy ballast (or attach a weight to your tether line), and see how far down it'll go without letting in water.

description.text:
This simple sticky pad holder was born out of necessity. I use a lot of sticky pads at work for marking up paperwork, flagging key pages in giant binders, writing down the day's tasks, etc. I wanted a one-handed sticky note solution for both sizes of sticky notes that my office stocks, so I took a lunch break and designed one.

This fits two sizes of sticky notes: The standard 3" x 3" sticky note, and the slightly less common 1.5" x 2" sticky note. I over-sized the compartments by .050" in each direction (e.g. 3.050" x 3.050" and 1.550" x 2.050") to accommodate for tolerances in the sticky note manufacturing process. I tested several different pads of both sizes, and they all seemed to fit pretty well.

I printed this on a Markforged Eiger Onyx One with 4 floor/ceiling layers, 2 wall layers, and 50% triangular infill. The filament I used was Onyx chopped carbon fiber filament.

Possible design improvements include:

  • Adding a recessed square on the bottom for a piece of double-sided tape
  • Slightly larger and/or lower cut-outs in the front for easier access
  • Thinner floor/walls for a faster print time
  • Increasing the height to stack multiple sticky pads

Happy printing!

After seeing several other gimbal designs (many less beefy than this one), I decided to try my hands at modeling something in Fusion360, using shelf pins that I happened to have laying around. There are probably better designs out there, but this is the one that I am using and it has eliminated z-banding for me.

You may also need to work with it a bit to get it installed. One of the other goals I had in designing this was to fix it to the frame in a way that would take some of the guesswork out of squaring up the two mounts. This was done using measurements from my printer, so I am sure there could be slight differences.

The shelf pins that I used were these, I believe:

https://www.amazon.com/Rok-Hardware-Shelf-Spoon-Nickel/dp/B00XWUQO3M/ref=sr_1_4?ie=UTF8&qid=1506554845&sr=8-4&keywords=shelf+pins

I did have to do some grinding on the ends of the shelf pins to prevent them from rubbing on the outer rings of the gimbal, but not much. If you don't have a grinder, you might be able to use a metal file - you'll probably be there a while, though.

Good luck!

comments.text: I originally used Slic3r and switched to Cura for the speed and the fact that cura lets you set a infill-to-perimeter overlap which makes nicer solid infill on the top of the prints (maybe Slic3r has added that since then, I don't know).  Also the retraction control in Cura seems to work better for me.  If you set Cura in the "full settings" mode (not quickprint) and then go to the expert options (Ctrl-E), there are several options for the brim you can change.  Also, under the advanced tab try changing the first layer speed (slower) and initial layer thickness to see if that helps your first layer.

description.text:
I got the inspiration from "Servo Protectors for ParkZone Radian Pro" by clough42, published Sep 29, 2014
However they were very large. I scaled them down then added a flat mounting surface for the 9g servo. You mount the servo where you want it using good servo mounting tape. Then secure the assembly into your wing with four #2 or 3mm screws. Makes changing or getting to the servo much easier and provides a fairing for the linkage. I have seen other 9g servo mounts here but they require more printing no fairing and are heavier.

Thanks again to clough42.

The file attached is for the right aileron. To print the left one just flip on the X-axis in your slicer program before printing. Cura does this nicely.

description.text:
The Hatchbox spool drawers work fabulous but I found myself spinning them around on my workbench to get at the drawer I wanted. So I designed a simple turntable to allow it to turn freely.

To that I added a simple joiner that permits me to stack more Hatchbox drawers in the future.

Notes:

The base will print just fine in the orientation in the file.

The groove for the bearings in the turntable top piece might or might not support depending on your printer. I printed with 4 perimeters and found I didn't need support. Mind you there's not much support needed anyway so it was easily removed when the print was done. The bearings (BB's) still rolled freely around the track.

Parts Used/Needed

In order for the turntable to rotate freely, and to keep any additional cost low, I used some air rifle BB's as the bearings.

In the top part of the turnable that fits into the slots on the Hatchbox spool, I drilled a 3.5mm hole. On the base, I drilled a 2.5mm hole. The single screw that is the axle is a M3 x 10. Don't over tighten it to the bottom, the top has to freely rotate.

description.text:
I was not able to find a wall mount that would fit the elite wireless controller (because of the paddles). So I went and designed my own.

I wanted a wall mount that would be lightweight, sturdy and easy to print.

I spent a couple of hours on Fusion 360 designing this, and yes, it's not perfect, so feedback is appreciated for v2! So please leave your comments!

Though depending on your printer, you might want to use support for those overhangs. For the prusa, I tried turning on the fans for those couple of layers to make sure that the filament would solidify quickly - no issues.

This was printed in AIO Robotic's PLA (I love that filament!).

I printed this at 0.10, 0.15 and 0,20 - They all looked good on the Prusa i3 MK2s.

Use Silicon / Rubber Tape

Since the elite wireless controller has a rubbery finish, depending on your filament/printer/print settings I was worried that the friction would damage the surface of the controllers. So i made the 'legs' flat so you can put some silicon/rubber tape on them.

If your tape is too thick, you might want to print at 101% or 102% scale.

I used 8mm head screws for this.

well I decided to go ahead and design my own version of Z anti wobble bracket with tensioning ... Now this should work to take out all wobble in Z. The main two parts will need supports when printed... These can be printed one at a time or both at the same time I included both options in the files.

What this design does is allow the Z axis lead screw to float in X and Y axis while maintaining Z axis. it also has the rear wheel able to move which would allow for it to be tightened against the 2020 rail removing any slack there as well.

Ok finally got this fully printed and a few minor changes made... should be good to go now...

I finally got this installed and it is working great... I have been putting it through it's passes. I changed one of the lead screw couplers with one that was bent out of shape and the lead screw base was moving 3-4 mm in all directions and I'm printing now and it is perfect print you can't even tell there is an issue with the coupler. photos of the part printed are done with the bent to heck coupler... so you can see that the part works

I just received a comment that the factory bolts are hitting the mounts so you might need to either flip the bolts around or trim the bolts end of the off flush with the end of the nut which is the way mine are.

UPDATE: ok after the comment about the bolts hitting I went ahead and added a relief cut on the top of each of the main 2 pieces these are under V2

Update: 12/3/17 OK I have been told there is an alignment issue with the X motor I use this on mine and have not had any issues so might want to print this as well https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2558147

UPDATE: 12/24/17 finally had time to update the design to lower the X 2020 rails 5mm to fix the alignment issues that where pointed out.

I printed out 3 different x motor mount plates I found here.
The problem that I'm having is that when the assembled, the X pulley should be aligned with the 2020 extrusion, so that the belt will fit in the slots and not drag. What is happening to me, is the motor ends up sitting lower on the horizontal, than the extrusion bar, the pulley not centred compared to the bar, which causes the belt to rub against the bar. (I mean there's too much room on the bottom, not enough room on the top. I know I keep bugging. Only because I like the basic idea, and am trying to get it to work for me.

comments.text:
What I'm talking about is the carriage plate/x motor mount. In other words, the other half of your z mount. It holds the wheels.
The stock item is 2 pieces.. a left hand side carriage plate that you attach the x motor to. when the carriages and z mounts are bolted through the hot end 2020 extrusion, if you look at the x motor pulley, it sits directly in-line with the 2020 beam. It does this, so the x-axis belt can go around the beam, without touching it. If I use your z mount/combo carriage plate with the stock left side X mount carriage plate. The x- motor becomes offset a bit LOWER than the hot end beam. This causes the belt, to rub against the TOP side of the beam. There are a number of x-mount/carriage plates here, I've printed and tried 3 of them, the problem is still the same, i'm unable to get the pulley aligned with the 2020 beam, and this causes the belt to rub along the top. However, it does not seem to affect your build, so I'm wondering what are you using on the opposite side of your s mount that holds the wheels and motor.
comments.author: DracenKnights

comments.text:
Are you using a custom X axis motor mount?
I ask because there's no way to use this with the stock one. The problem is that this z mount will cause belt/gantry interference if used with the stock outer plate. The stock mounts use a slot for adjustment, however your solution is fixed, allowing no up or down adjustment. The belt has to travel smoothly across the top and bottom of the gantry. I see in your picture you have a 3d printed X-mount.
Please tell us which one it is.
Thanks
